# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biophysics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Bioenergetics is the part of biochemistry concerned with the energy involved in making and breaking of chemical bonds in the molecules found in biological organisms.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] It can also be defined as the study of energy relationships and energy transformations and transductions in living organisms.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The ability to harness energy from a variety of metabolic pathways is a property of all living organisms.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Growth, development, anabolism and catabolism are some of the central processes in the study of biological organisms, because the role of energy is fundamental to such biological processes.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Life is dependent on energy transformations; living organisms survive because of exchange of energy between living tissues/cells and the outside environment.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Some organisms, such as autotrophs, can acquire energy from sunlight (through photosynthesis) without needing to consume nutrients and break them down.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Other organisms, like heterotrophs, must intake nutrients from food to be able to sustain energy by breaking down chemical bonds in nutrients during metabolic processes such as glycolysis and the citric acid cycle.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Importantly, as a direct consequence of the first law of thermodynamics, autotrophs and heterotrophs participate in a universal metabolic network—by eating autotrophs (plants), heterotrophs harness energy that was initially transformed by the plants during photosynthesis.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] In a living organism, chemical bonds are broken and made as part of the exchange and transformation of energy.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Energy is available for work (such as mechanical work) or for other processes (such as chemical synthesis and anabolic processes in growth), when weak bonds are broken and stronger bonds are made.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The production of stronger bonds allows release of usable energy.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] In a cell, the ratio of ATP to ADP concentrations is known as the "energy charge" of the cell.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] A cell can use this energy charge to relay information about cellular needs; if there is more ATP than ADP available, the cell can use ATP to do work, but if there is more ADP than ATP available, the cell must synthesize ATP via oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Living organisms produce ATP from energy sources via oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The terminal phosphate bonds of ATP are relatively weak compared with the stronger bonds formed when ATP is hydrolyzed (broken down by water) to adenosine diphosphate and inorganic phosphate.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Here it is the thermodynamically favorable free energy of hydrolysis that results in energy release; the phosphoanhydride bond between the terminal phosphate group and the rest of the ATP molecule does not itself contain this energy.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] An organism's stockpile of ATP is used as a battery to store energy in cells.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Utilization of chemical energy from such molecular bond rearrangement powers biological processes in every biological organism.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Living organisms obtain energy from organic and inorganic materials; i.e.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] ATP can be synthesized from a variety of biochemical precursors.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] For example, lithotrophs can oxidize minerals such as nitrates or forms of sulfur, such as elemental sulfur, sulfites, and hydrogen sulfide to produce ATP.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] In photosynthesis, autotrophs produce ATP using light energy, whereas heterotrophs must consume organic compounds, mostly including carbohydrates, fats, and proteins.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The amount of energy actually obtained by the organism is lower than the amount present in the food; there are losses in digestion, metabolism, and thermogenesis.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Environmental materials that an organism intakes are generally combined with oxygen to release energy, although some nutrients can also be oxidized anaerobically by various organisms.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The utilization of these materials is a form of slow combustion because the nutrients are reacted with oxygen (the materials are oxidized slowly enough that the organisms do not produce fire).
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The oxidation releases energy, which may evolve as heat or be used by the organism for other purposes, such as breaking chemical bonds.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The free energy (Δ*G*) gained or lost in a reaction can be calculated as follows: Δ*G* = Δ*H* − *T*Δ*S* where ∆*G* = Gibbs free energy, ∆*H* = enthalpy, *T* = temperature (in kelvins), and ∆*S* = entropy.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Is the **linkage** of chemical reactions in a way that the product of one reaction becomes the substrate of another reaction.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Crane presented for the first time his discovery of the sodium-glucose cotransport as the mechanism for intestinal glucose absorption.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Crane's discovery of cotransport was the first ever proposal of flux coupling in biology and was the most important event concerning carbohydrate absorption in the 20th century.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] One of the major triumphs of bioenergetics is Peter D.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Mitchell's chemiosmotic theory of how protons in aqueous solution function in the production of ATP in cell organelles such as mitochondria.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] This work earned Mitchell the 1978 Nobel Prize for Chemistry.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Other cellular sources of ATP such as glycolysis were understood first, but such processes for direct coupling of enzyme activity to ATP production are not the major source of useful chemical energy in most cells.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Chemiosmotic coupling is the major energy producing process in most cells, being utilized in chloroplasts and several single celled organisms in addition to mitochondria.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The binding change mechanism, proposed by Paul Boyer and John E.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Walker, who were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1997, suggests that ATP synthesis is linked to a conformational change in ATP synthase.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] This change is triggered by the rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] ATP synthesis can be achieved through several mechanisms.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] The first mechanism postulates that the free energy of the proton gradient is utilized to alter the conformation of polypeptide molecules in the ATP synthesis active centers.
[src:biophysics/bioenergetics] Energy homeostasis is the homeostatic control of energy balance – the difference between energy obtained through food consumption and energy expenditure – in living systems.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Molecular biophysics typically addresses biological questions similar to those in biochemistry and molecular biology, seeking to find the physical underpinnings of biomolecular phenomena.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Scientists in this field conduct research concerned with understanding the interactions between the various systems of a cell, including the interactions between DNA, RNA and protein biosynthesis, as well as how these interactions are regulated.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] A great variety of techniques are used to answer these questions.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Biophysics covers all scales of biological organization, from molecular to organismic and populations.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Biophysical research shares significant overlap with biochemistry, molecular biology, physical chemistry, physiology, nanotechnology, bioengineering, computational biology, biomechanics, developmental biology and systems biology.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Fluorescent imaging techniques, as well as electron microscopy, x-ray crystallography, NMR spectroscopy, atomic force microscopy (AFM) and small-angle scattering (SAS).
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Small-angle X-ray scattering and small-angle neutron scattering (SAXS/SANS) are often used to visualize structures of biological significance.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Protein dynamics can be observed by neutron spin echo spectroscopy.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Conformational changes in structure can be measured using techniques such as dual polarisation interferometry, circular dichroism, SAXS and SANS.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Direct manipulation of molecules using optical tweezers or AFM, can also be used to monitor biological events where forces and distances are at the nanoscale.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Molecular biophysicists often consider complex biological events as systems of interacting entities which can be understood e.g. through statistical mechanics, thermodynamics and chemical kinetics.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] By drawing knowledge and experimental techniques from a wide variety of disciplines, biophysicists are often able to directly observe, model or even manipulate the structures and interactions of individual molecules or complexes of molecules.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Medical physics, a branch of biophysics, is any application of physics to medicine or healthcare, ranging from radiology to microscopy and nanomedicine.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] For example, physicist Richard Feynman theorized about the future of nanomedicine.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] He wrote about the idea of a *medical* use for biological machines (see nanomachines).
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Feynman and Albert Hibbs suggested that certain repair machines might one day be reduced in size to the point that it would be possible to (as Feynman put it) "swallow the doctor".
[src:biophysics/biophysics] The idea was discussed in Feynman's 1959 essay *There's Plenty of Room at the Bottom*.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] The term *biophysics* is also regularly used in academia to indicate the study of the physical quantities (e.g. electric current, temperature, stress, entropy) in biological systems.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Other biological sciences also perform research on the biophysical properties of living organisms including molecular biology, cell biology, chemical biology, and biochemistry.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] In addition to traditional (i.e. molecular and cellular) biophysical topics like structural biology or enzyme kinetics, modern biophysics encompasses an extraordinarily broad range of research, from bioelectronics to quantum biology involving both experimental and theoretical tools.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] It is becoming increasingly common for biophysicists to apply the models and experimental techniques derived from physics, as well as mathematics and statistics, to larger systems such as tissues, organs, populations and ecosystems.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Biophysical models are used extensively in the study of electrical conduction in single neurons, as well as neural circuit analysis in both tissue and whole brain.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] The studies of Luigi Galvani (1737–1798) laid groundwork for the later field of biophysics.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Some of the earlier studies in biophysics were conducted in the 1840s by a group known as the Berlin school of physiologists.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Among its members were pioneers such as Hermann von Helmholtz, Ernst Heinrich Weber, Carl F.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] The term *biophysics* was originally introduced by Karl Pearson in 1892.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Bovie (1882–1958) is credited as a leader of the field's further development in the mid-20th century.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] He was a leader in developing electrosurgery.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] The popularity of the field rose when the book *What Is Life?* by Erwin Schrödinger was published.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Since 1957, biophysicists have organized themselves into the Biophysical Society which now has about 9,000 members over the world.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Some authors such as Robert Rosen criticize biophysics on the ground that the biophysical method does not take into account the specificity of biological phenomena.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Depending on the strengths of a department at a university differing emphasis will be given to fields of biophysics.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] What follows is a list of examples of how each department applies its efforts toward the study of biophysics.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Nor does each subject of study belong exclusively to any particular department.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Each academic institution makes its own rules and there is much overlap between departments.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Many biophysical techniques are unique to this field.
[src:biophysics/biophysics] Research efforts in biophysics are often initiated by scientists who were biologists, chemists or physicists by training.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The study of ion channels often involves biophysics, electrophysiology, and pharmacology, while using techniques including voltage clamp, patch clamp, immunohistochemistry, X-ray crystallography, fluoroscopy, and RT-PCR.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Their classification as molecules is referred to as channelomics.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ions pass through channels down their electrochemical gradient, which is a function of ion concentration and membrane potential, "downhill", without the input (or help) of metabolic energy (e.g.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] ATP, co-transport mechanisms, or active transport mechanisms).
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ion channels are located within the membrane of all excitable cells, and of many intracellular organelles.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] They are often described as narrow, water-filled tunnels that allow only ions of a certain size and/or charge to pass through.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] This characteristic is called selective permeability.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The archetypal channel pore is just one or two atoms wide at its narrowest point and is selective for specific species of ion, such as sodium or potassium.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] However, some channels may be permeable to the passage of more than one type of ion, typically sharing a common charge: positive (cations) or negative (anions).
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ions often move through the segments of the channel pore in a single file nearly as quickly as the ions move through the free solution.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] In many ion channels, passage through the pore is governed by a "gate", which may be opened or closed in response to chemical or electrical signals, temperature, or mechanical force.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ion channels are integral membrane proteins, typically formed as assemblies of several individual proteins.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Such "multi-subunit" assemblies usually involve a circular arrangement of identical or homologous proteins closely packed around a water-filled pore through the plane of the membrane or lipid bilayer.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] For most voltage-gated ion channels, the pore-forming subunit(s) are called the α subunit, while the auxiliary subunits are denoted β, γ, and so on.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Because channels underlie the nerve impulse and because "transmitter-activated" channels mediate conduction across the synapses, channels are especially prominent components of the nervous system.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Indeed, numerous toxins that organisms have evolved for shutting down the nervous systems of predators and prey (e.g., the venoms produced by spiders, scorpions, snakes, fish, bees, sea snails, and others) work by modulating ion channel conductance and/or kinetics.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] In addition, ion channels are key components in a wide variety of biological processes that involve rapid changes in cells, such as cardiac, skeletal, and smooth muscle contraction, epithelial transport of nutrients and ions, T-cell activation, and pancreatic beta-cell insulin release.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] In the search for new drugs, ion channels are a frequent target.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] There are over 300 types of ion channels just in the cells of the inner ear.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ion channels may be classified by the nature of their gating, the species of ions passing through those gates, the number of gates (pores), and localization of proteins.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Further heterogeneity of ion channels arises when channels with different constitutive subunits give rise to a specific kind of current.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Absence or mutation of one or more of the contributing types of channel subunits can result in loss of function and, potentially, underlie neurologic diseases.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ion channels may be classified by gating, i.e. what opens and closes the channels.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] For example, voltage-gated ion channels open or close depending on the voltage gradient across the plasma membrane, while ligand-gated ion channels open or close depending on binding of ligands to the channel.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Voltage-gated ion channels open and close in response to membrane potential.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Also known as ionotropic receptors, this group of channels open in response to specific ligand molecules binding to the extracellular domain of the receptor protein.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ligand binding causes a conformational change in the structure of the channel protein that ultimately leads to the opening of the channel gate and subsequent ion flux across the plasma membrane.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Examples of such channels include the cation-permeable nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, ionotropic glutamate-gated receptors, acid-sensing ion channels (ASICs), ATP-gated P2X receptors, and the anion-permeable γ-aminobutyric acid-gated GABAA receptor.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ion channels activated by second messengers may also be categorized in this group, although ligands and second messengers are otherwise distinguished from each other.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] This group of channels opens in response to specific lipid molecules binding to the channel's transmembrane domain typically near the inner leaflet of the plasma membrane.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate (PIP2) and phosphatidic acid (PA) are the best-characterized lipids to gate these channels.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Many of the leak potassium channels are gated by lipids including the inward-rectifier potassium channels and two pore domain potassium channels TREK-1 and TRAAK.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] KCNQ potassium channel family are gated by PIP2.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The voltage activated potassium channel (Kv) is regulated by PA.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Its midpoint of activation shifts +50 mV upon PA hydrolysis, near resting membrane potentials.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] This suggests Kv could be opened by lipid hydrolysis independent of voltage and may qualify this channel as dual lipid and voltage gated channel.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Gating also includes activation and inactivation by second messengers from the inside of the cell membrane – rather than from outside the cell, as in the case for ligands.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ion channels are also classified according to their subcellular localization.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The plasma membrane accounts for around 2% of the total membrane in the cell, whereas intracellular organelles contain 98% of the cell's membrane.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The major intracellular compartments are endoplasmic reticulum, Golgi apparatus, and mitochondria.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Channels differ with respect to the ion they let pass (for example, Na+, K+, Cl−), the ways in which they may be regulated, the number of subunits of which they are composed and other aspects of structure.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Channels belonging to the largest class, which includes the voltage-gated channels that underlie the nerve impulse, consist of four or sometimes five subunits with six transmembrane helices each.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] On activation, these helices move about and open the pore.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Two of these six helices are separated by a loop that lines the pore and is the primary determinant of ion selectivity and conductance in this channel class and some others.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The existence and mechanism for ion selectivity was first postulated in the late 1960s by Bertil Hille and Clay Armstrong.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] This mechanism was finally confirmed when the first structure of an ion channel was elucidated.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] A bacterial potassium channel KcsA, consisting of just the selectivity filter, "P" loop, and two transmembrane helices was used as a model to study the permeability and the selectivity of ion channels in the Mackinnon lab.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The determination of the molecular structure of KcsA by Roderick MacKinnon using X-ray crystallography won a share of the 2003 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] An example is the long-awaited crystal structure of a voltage-gated potassium channel, which was reported in May 2003.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] One inevitable ambiguity about these structures relates to the strong evidence that channels change conformation as they operate (they open and close, for example), such that the structure in the crystal could represent any one of these operational states.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Most of what researchers have deduced about channel operation so far they have established through electrophysiology, biochemistry, gene sequence comparison and mutagenesis.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Channels can have single (CLICs) to multiple transmembrane (K channels, P2X receptors, Na channels) domains which span plasma membrane to form pores.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Pore can determine the selectivity of the channel.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Gate can be formed either inside or outside the pore region.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Chemical substances can modulate the activity of ion channels, for example by blocking or activating them.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] A variety of ion channel blockers (inorganic and organic molecules) can modulate ion channel activity and conductance.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Several compounds are known to promote the opening or activation of specific ion channels.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] There are a number of disorders which disrupt normal functioning of ion channels and have disastrous consequences for the organism.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Genetic and autoimmune disorders of ion channels and their modifiers are known as channelopathies.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] See Category:Channelopathies for a full list.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The fundamental properties of currents mediated by ion channels were analyzed by the British biophysicists Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley as part of their Nobel Prize-winning research on the action potential, published in 1952.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] They built on the work of other physiologists, such as Cole and Baker's research into voltage-gated membrane pores from 1941.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The existence of ion channels was confirmed in the 1970s by Bernard Katz and Ricardo Miledi using noise analysis.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] It was then shown more directly with an electrical recording technique known as the "patch clamp", which led to a Nobel Prize to Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann, the technique's inventors.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Hundreds if not thousands of researchers continue to pursue a more detailed understanding of how these proteins work.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] In recent years the development of automated patch clamp devices helped to increase significantly the throughput in ion channel screening.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The Nobel Prize in Chemistry for 2003 was awarded to Roderick MacKinnon for his studies on the physico-chemical properties of ion channel structure and function, including x-ray crystallographic structure studies.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Roderick MacKinnon commissioned *Birth of an Idea*, a 5-foot (1.5 m) tall sculpture based on the KcsA potassium channel.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The artwork, by Julian Voss-Andreae, contains a wire object representing the channel's interior with a blown glass object representing the main cavity of the channel structure.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] The behavior of ion channels can be usefully modeled using mathematics and probability.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Stochastic processes are mathematical models of systems and phenomena that appear to vary in a random manner.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] A very simple example is flipping a coin; each flip has an equal chance to be heads or tails, the chances are not influenced by the outcome of past flips, and we can say that pheads = 0.5 and ptails = 0.5.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] A particularly relevant form of stochastic processes in the study of ion channels is Markov chains.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] In a Markov chain, there are multiple states, each of which has given chances to transition to different states over a particular period of time.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Ion channels undergo state transitions (e.g. open, closed, inactive) that behave like Markov chains.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Markov chain analysis can be used to make conclusions regarding the nature of a given ion channel, including the likely number of open and closed states.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] We can also use Markov chain analysis to produce models that accurately simulate the insertion of ion channels into cell membranes.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Markov chains can also be used in combination with the stochastic matrix to determine the stable distribution matrix by solving the equation PX=X, where P is the stochastic matrix and X is the stable distribution matrix.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] This stable distribution matrix tells us the relative frequencies of each state after a long time, which in the context of ion channels can be the frequencies of the open, closed, and inactive states for an ion channel.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Note that Markov chain assumptions apply, including that (1) all transition probabilities for each state sum to one, (2) the probability model applies to all possible states, and (3) that the probability of transitions are constant over time.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] Therefore, Markov chains have limited applicability in some situations.
[src:biophysics/ion-channel] There are a variety of other stochastic processes that are utilized in the study of ion channels, but are too complex to relate here and can be examined more closely elsewhere.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] By convention it is written as Vm=Vinside−Voutside, so a negative membrane potential means the cell interior is negative relative to the outside.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Essentially, It equals the interior potential minus the exterior potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This is the energy per charge which is required to move a very small positive charge at constant velocity across the cell membrane from the exterior to the interior.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Note, though, that if the charge is allowed to change velocity, the change of kinetic energy and production of radiation must be taken into account.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Typical values of membrane potential is normally given in units of millivolts and denoted as mV.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In many animal cells, Vm is typically in the order of tens of millivolts.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] It commonly falls in the range of about −20 mV to −200 mV depending on the cell type and state.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For such typical negative membrane potentials, positive work is required to move a positive charge from the interior to the exterior.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] However, thermal kinetic energy allows ions to overcome the potential difference.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For a selectively permeable membrane, this permits a net flow against the gradient.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Although the entire cell is considered negative inside, the fluids in the cell are electrically neutral.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The presence of the voltage is due to the thin layer of charge that accumulates at the surfaces of the cell membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The cell membrane is only a few nanometers thick, and as such, even a voltage of 100 mV across this thickness generates an electric field that is extremely strong on the cell membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] All animal cells are surrounded by a membrane composed of a lipid bilayer with proteins embedded in it.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The membrane serves both as a capacitor and as a diffusion barrier to the movement of ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ion pumps actively push ions across the membrane and establish concentration gradients across the membrane, and ion channels allow ions to move across the membrane down their electrochemical gradients.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ion channels and ion pumps are transmembrane proteins, and are electrically analogous to resistors and current sources (batteries), and contribute to the voltage across the two sides of the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] All plasma membranes have an electrical potential across them, with the inside usually negative with respect to the outside.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The membrane potential has two basic functions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] First, it allows a cell to function as a battery, providing power to operate a variety of "molecular devices" embedded in the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Second, in electrically **excitable cells** such as neurons and muscle cells, it is used for transmitting signals between different parts of a cell.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Signals are generated in excitable cells by opening or closing of ion channels at one point in the membrane, producing a local change in the membrane potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This change in the electric field can be quickly sensed by either adjacent or more distant ion channels in the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Those ion channels can then open or close as a result of the potential change, reproducing the signal.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In non-excitable cells, and in excitable cells in their baseline states, the membrane potential is held at a relatively stable value, called the resting potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For neurons, resting potential is defined as ranging from −80 to −70 millivolts; that is, the interior of a cell has a negative baseline voltage of a bit less than one-tenth of a volt.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The opening and closing of ion channels can induce a departure from the resting potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This is called a depolarization if the interior voltage becomes less negative (say from −70 mV to −60 mV), or a hyperpolarization if the interior voltage becomes more negative (say from −70 mV to −80 mV).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In excitable cells, a sufficiently large depolarization can evoke an action potential, in which the membrane potential changes rapidly and significantly for a short time (on the order of 1 to 100 milliseconds), often reversing its polarity.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Action potentials are generated by the activation of certain voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In neurons, the factors that influence the membrane potential are diverse.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] They include numerous types of ion channels, some of which are chemically gated and some of which are voltage-gated.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Because voltage-gated ion channels are controlled by the membrane potential, while the membrane potential itself is influenced by these same ion channels, feedback loops that allow for complex temporal dynamics arise, including oscillations and regenerative events such as action potentials.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Differences in the concentrations of ions on opposite sides of a cellular membrane lead to a voltage called the **membrane potential**.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Many ions have a concentration gradient across the membrane, including potassium (K+), which is at a high concentration inside and a low concentration outside the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Sodium (Na+) and chloride (Cl−) ions are at high concentrations in the extracellular region, and low concentrations in the intracellular regions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] These concentration gradients provide the potential energy to drive the formation of the membrane potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This voltage is established when the membrane has permeability to one or more ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In the simplest case, illustrated in the top diagram ("Ion concentration gradients"), if the membrane is selectively permeable to potassium, these positively charged ions can diffuse down the concentration gradient to the outside of the cell, leaving behind uncompensated negative charges.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This separation of charges is what causes the membrane potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The system as a whole is electro-neutral.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The uncompensated positive charges outside the cell, and the uncompensated negative charges inside the cell, physically line up on the membrane surface and attract each other across the lipid bilayer.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Thus, the membrane potential is physically located only in the immediate vicinity of the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] It is the separation of these charges across the membrane that is the basis of the membrane voltage.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The top diagram is only an approximation of the ionic contributions to the membrane potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Other ions including sodium, chloride, calcium, and others play a more minor role, even though they have strong concentration gradients, because they have more limited permeability than potassium.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The membrane potential in a cell derives ultimately from two factors: electrical force and diffusion.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Electrical force arises from the mutual attraction between particles with opposite electrical charges (positive and negative) and the mutual repulsion between particles with the same type of charge (both positive or both negative).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Diffusion arises from the statistical tendency of particles to redistribute from regions where they are highly concentrated to regions where the concentration is low.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Voltage, which is synonymous with *difference in electrical potential*, is the ability to drive an electric current across a resistance.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Indeed, the simplest definition of a voltage is given by Ohm's law: V=IR, where V is voltage, I is current and R is resistance.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] If a voltage source such as a battery is placed in an electrical circuit, the higher the voltage of the source the greater the amount of current that it will drive across the available resistance.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The functional significance of voltage lies only in potential *differences* between two points in a circuit.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The idea of a voltage at a single point is meaningless.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] It is conventional in electronics to assign a voltage of zero to some arbitrarily chosen element of the circuit, and then assign voltages for other elements measured relative to that zero point.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] There is no significance in which element is chosen as the zero point—the function of a circuit depends only on the differences not on voltages *per se*.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] However, in most cases and by convention, the zero level is most often assigned to the portion of a circuit that is in contact with ground.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The same principle applies to voltage in cell biology.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In electrically active tissue, the potential difference between any two points can be measured by inserting an electrode at each point, for example one inside and one outside the cell, and connecting both electrodes to the leads of what is in essence a specialized voltmeter.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] By convention, the zero potential value is assigned to the outside of the cell and the sign of the potential difference between the outside and the inside is determined by the potential of the inside relative to the outside zero.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In mathematical terms, the definition of voltage begins with the concept of an electric field **E**, a vector field assigning a magnitude and direction to each point in space.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In many situations, the electric field is a conservative field, which means that it can be expressed as the gradient of a scalar function *V*, that is, **E** = −∇*V*.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This scalar field *V* is referred to as the voltage distribution.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The definition allows for an arbitrary constant of integration—this is why absolute values of voltage are not meaningful.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In general, electric fields can be treated as conservative only if magnetic fields do not significantly influence them, but this condition usually applies well to biological tissue.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Because the electric field is the gradient of the voltage distribution, rapid changes in voltage within a small region imply a strong electric field; on the converse, if the voltage remains approximately the same over a large region, the electric fields in that region must be weak.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A strong electric field, equivalent to a strong voltage gradient, implies that a strong force is exerted on any charged particles that lie within the region.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Electrical signals within biological organisms are, in general, driven by ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The most important cations for the action potential are sodium (Na+) and potassium (K+).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Both of these are *monovalent* cations that carry a single positive charge.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Action potentials can also involve calcium (Ca2+), which is a *divalent* cation that carries a double positive charge.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The chloride anion (Cl−) plays a major role in the action potentials of some algae, but plays a negligible role in the action potentials of most animals.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ions cross the cell membrane under two influences: diffusion and electric fields.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A simple example wherein two solutions—A and B—are separated by a porous barrier illustrates that diffusion will ensure that they will eventually mix into equal solutions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This mixing occurs because of the difference in their concentrations.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The region with high concentration will diffuse out toward the region with low concentration.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] To extend the example, let solution A have 30 sodium ions and 30 chloride ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Also, let solution B have only 20 sodium ions and 20 chloride ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Assuming the barrier allows both types of ions to travel through it, then a steady state will be reached whereby both solutions have 25 sodium ions and 25 chloride ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] If, however, the porous barrier is selective to which ions are let through, then diffusion alone will not determine the resulting solution.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Returning to the previous example, let's now construct a barrier that is permeable only to sodium ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Now, only sodium is allowed to diffuse cross the barrier from its higher concentration in solution A to the lower concentration in solution B.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This will result in a greater accumulation of sodium ions than chloride ions in solution B and a lesser number of sodium ions than chloride ions in solution A.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This means that there is a net positive charge in solution B from the higher concentration of positively charged sodium ions than negatively charged chloride ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Likewise, there is a net negative charge in solution A from the greater concentration of negative chloride ions than positive sodium ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Since opposite charges attract and like charges repel, the ions are now also influenced by electrical fields as well as forces of diffusion.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Therefore, positive sodium ions will be less likely to travel to the now-more-positive B solution and remain in the now-more-negative A solution.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The point at which the forces of the electric fields completely counteract the force due to diffusion is called the equilibrium potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] At this point, the net flow of the specific ion (in this case sodium) is zero.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Every cell is enclosed in a plasma membrane, which has the structure of a lipid bilayer with many types of large molecules embedded in it.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Because it is made of lipid molecules, the plasma membrane intrinsically has a high electrical resistivity, in other words a low intrinsic permeability to ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] However, some of the molecules embedded in the membrane are capable either of actively transporting ions from one side of the membrane to the other or of providing channels through which they can move.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In electrical terminology, the plasma membrane functions as a combined resistor and capacitor.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Resistance arises from the fact that the membrane impedes the movement of charges across it.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Capacitance arises from the fact that the lipid bilayer is so thin that an accumulation of charged particles on one side gives rise to an electrical force that pulls oppositely charged particles toward the other side.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The capacitance of the membrane is relatively unaffected by the molecules that are embedded in it, so it has a more or less invariant value estimated at 2 μF/cm2 (the total capacitance of a patch of membrane is proportional to its area).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The conductance of a pure lipid bilayer is so low, on the other hand, that in biological situations it is always dominated by the conductance of alternative pathways provided by embedded molecules.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Thus, the capacitance of the membrane is more or less fixed, but the resistance is highly variable.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The thickness of a plasma membrane is estimated to be about 7–8 nanometers.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Because the membrane is so thin, it does not take a very large transmembrane voltage to create a strong electric field within it.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The resistance of a pure lipid bilayer to the passage of ions across it is very high, but structures embedded in the membrane can greatly enhance ion movement, either actively or passively.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This is achieved via the mechanisms of active transport and facilitated diffusion.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The two types of structure that play the largest roles are ion channels and ion pumps, both usually formed from assemblages of protein molecules.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ion channels provide passageways through which ions can move.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In most cases, an ion channel is permeable only to specific types of ions (for example, sodium and potassium but not chloride or calcium), and sometimes the permeability varies depending on the direction of ion movement.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ion pumps, also known as ion transporters or carrier proteins, actively transport specific types of ions from one side of the membrane to the other, sometimes using energy derived from metabolic processes to do so.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ion pumps are integral membrane proteins that carry out active transport, i.e., use cellular energy (ATP) to "pump" the ions against their concentration gradient.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Such ion pumps take in ions from one side of the membrane (decreasing its concentration there) and release them on the other side (increasing its concentration there).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The ion pump most relevant to the action potential is the sodium–potassium pump, which transports three sodium ions out of the cell and two potassium ions in.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] As a consequence, the concentration of potassium ions K+ inside the neuron is roughly 30-fold larger than the outside concentration, whereas the sodium concentration outside is roughly five-fold larger than inside.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In a similar manner, other ions have different concentrations inside and outside the neuron, such as calcium, chloride and magnesium.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The sodium-potassium pump is relatively slow in operation.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] If a cell were initialized with equal concentrations of sodium and potassium everywhere, it would take hours for the pump to establish equilibrium.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The pump operates constantly, but becomes progressively less efficient as the concentrations of sodium and potassium available for pumping are reduced.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ion pumps influence the action potential only by establishing the relative ratio of intracellular and extracellular ion concentrations.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The action potential involves mainly the opening and closing of ion channels not ion pumps.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] If the ion pumps are turned off by removing their energy source, or by adding an inhibitor such as ouabain, the axon can still fire hundreds of thousands of action potentials before their amplitudes begin to decay significantly.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In particular, ion pumps play no significant role in the repolarization of the membrane after an action potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Another functionally important ion pump is the sodium-calcium exchanger.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This pump operates in a conceptually similar way to the sodium-potassium pump, except that in each cycle it exchanges three Na+ from the extracellular space for one Ca++ from the intracellular space.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Because the net flow of charge is inward, this pump runs "downhill", in effect, and therefore does not require any energy source except the membrane voltage.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Its most important effect is to pump calcium outward—it also allows an inward flow of sodium, thereby counteracting the sodium-potassium pump, but, because overall sodium and potassium concentrations are much higher than calcium concentrations, this effect is relatively unimportant.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The net result of the sodium-calcium exchanger is that in the resting state, intracellular calcium concentrations become very low.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ion channels are integral membrane proteins with a pore through which ions can travel between extracellular space and cell interior.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Most channels are specific (selective) for one ion; for example, most potassium channels are characterized by 1000:1 selectivity ratio for potassium over sodium, though potassium and sodium ions have the same charge and differ only slightly in their radius.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The channel pore is typically so small that ions must pass through it in single-file order.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Channel pores can be either open or closed for ion passage, although a number of channels demonstrate various sub-conductance levels.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] When a channel is open, ions permeate through the channel pore down the transmembrane concentration gradient for that particular ion.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Rate of ionic flow through the channel, i.e. single-channel current amplitude, is determined by the maximum channel conductance and electrochemical driving force for that ion, which is the difference between the instantaneous value of the membrane potential and the value of the reversal potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A channel may have several different states (corresponding to different conformations of the protein), but each such state is either open or closed.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In general, closed states correspond either to a contraction of the pore—making it impassable to the ion—or to a separate part of the protein, stoppering the pore.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For example, the voltage-dependent sodium channel undergoes *inactivation*, in which a portion of the protein swings into the pore, sealing it.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This inactivation shuts off the sodium current and plays a critical role in the action potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ion channels can be classified by how they respond to their environment.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For example, the ion channels involved in the action potential are *voltage-sensitive channels*; they open and close in response to the voltage across the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] *Ligand-gated channels* form another important class; these ion channels open and close in response to the binding of a ligand molecule, such as a neurotransmitter.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Other ion channels open and close with mechanical forces.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Still other ion channels—such as those of sensory neurons—open and close in response to other stimuli, such as light, temperature or pressure.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Leakage channels are the simplest type of ion channel, in that their permeability is more or less constant.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The types of leakage channels that have the greatest significance in neurons are potassium and chloride channels.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Ligand-gated ion channels are channels whose permeability is greatly increased when some type of chemical ligand binds to the protein structure.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Animal cells contain hundreds, if not thousands, of types of these.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A large subset function as neurotransmitter receptors—they occur at postsynaptic sites, and the chemical ligand that gates them is released by the presynaptic axon terminal.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] One example of this type is the AMPA receptor, a receptor for the neurotransmitter glutamate that when activated allows passage of sodium and potassium ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Another example is the GABAA receptor, a receptor for the neurotransmitter GABA that when activated allows passage of chloride ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Neurotransmitter receptors are activated by ligands that appear in the extracellular area, but there are other types of ligand-gated channels that are controlled by interactions on the intracellular side.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Voltage-gated ion channels, also known as *voltage dependent ion channels*, are channels whose permeability is influenced by the membrane potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] They form another very large group, with each member having a particular ion selectivity and a particular voltage dependence.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Many are also time-dependent—in other words, they do not respond immediately to a voltage change but only after a delay.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The channel is closed at the resting voltage level, but opens abruptly when the voltage exceeds a certain threshold, allowing a large influx of sodium ions that produces a very rapid change in the membrane potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Recovery from an action potential is partly dependent on a type of voltage-gated potassium channel that is closed at the resting voltage level but opens as a consequence of the large voltage change produced during the action potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The reversal potential (or *equilibrium potential*) of an ion is the value of transmembrane voltage at which diffusive and electrical forces counterbalance, so that there is no net ion flow across the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This means that the transmembrane voltage exactly opposes the force of diffusion of the ion, such that the net current of the ion across the membrane is zero and unchanging.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The reversal potential is important because it gives the voltage that acts on channels permeable to that ion—in other words, it gives the voltage that the ion concentration gradient generates when it acts as a battery.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The equilibrium potential of a particular ion is usually designated by the notation *E*ion.The equilibrium potential for any ion can be calculated using the Nernst equation.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Even if two different ions have the same charge (i.e., K+ and Na+), they can still have very different equilibrium potentials, provided their outside and/or inside concentrations differ.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Take, for example, the equilibrium potentials of potassium and sodium in neurons.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The potassium equilibrium potential *E*K is −84 mV with 5 mM potassium outside and 140 mM inside.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] On the other hand, the sodium equilibrium potential, *E*Na, is approximately +66 mV with approximately 12 mM sodium inside and 140 mM outside.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A neuron's resting membrane potential actually changes during the development of an organism.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In order for a neuron to eventually adopt its full adult function, its potential must be tightly regulated during development.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] As an organism progresses through development the resting membrane potential becomes more negative.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Glial cells are also differentiating and proliferating as development progresses in the brain.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The addition of these glial cells increases the organism's ability to regulate extracellular potassium.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The drop in extracellular potassium can lead to a decrease in membrane potential of 35 mV.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Cell excitability is the change in membrane potential that is necessary for cellular responses in various tissues.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Cell excitability is a property that is induced during early embryogenesis.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Excitability of a cell has also been defined as the ease with which a response may be triggered.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The resting and threshold potentials forms the basis of cell excitability and these processes are fundamental for the generation of graded and action potentials.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The most important regulators of cell excitability are the extracellular electrolyte concentrations (i.e.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Na+, K+, Ca2+, Cl−, Mg2+) and associated proteins.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Important proteins that regulate cell excitability are voltage-gated ion channels, ion transporters (e.g.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Na+/K+-ATPase, magnesium transporters, acid–base transporters), membrane receptors and hyperpolarization-activated cyclic-nucleotide-gated channels.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For example, potassium channels and calcium-sensing receptors are important regulators of excitability in neurons, cardiac myocytes and many other excitable cells like astrocytes.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Calcium ion is also the most important second messenger in excitable cell signaling.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Activation of synaptic receptors initiates long-lasting changes in neuronal excitability.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Thyroid, adrenal and other hormones also regulate cell excitability, for example, progesterone and estrogen modulate myometrial smooth muscle cell excitability.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Many cell types are considered to have an excitable membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Astrocytes display a form of non-electrical excitability based on intracellular calcium variations related to the expression of several receptors through which they can detect the synaptic signal.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In neurons, there are different membrane properties in some portions of the cell, for example, dendritic excitability endows neurons with the capacity for coincidence detection of spatially separated inputs.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Electrophysiologists model the effects of ionic concentration differences, ion channels, and membrane capacitance in terms of an equivalent circuit, which is intended to represent the electrical properties of a small patch of membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The equivalent circuit consists of a capacitor in parallel with four pathways each consisting of a battery in series with a variable conductance.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The capacitance is determined by the properties of the lipid bilayer, and is taken to be fixed.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Each of the four parallel pathways comes from one of the principal ions, sodium, potassium, chloride, and calcium.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The voltage of each ionic pathway is determined by the concentrations of the ion on each side of the membrane; see the Reversal potential section above.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The conductance of each ionic pathway at any point in time is determined by the states of all the ion channels that are potentially permeable to that ion, including leakage channels, ligand-gated channels, and voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For fixed ion concentrations and fixed values of ion channel conductance, the equivalent circuit can be further reduced, using the Goldman equation as described below, to a circuit containing a capacitance in parallel with a battery and conductance.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In electrical terms, this is a type of RC circuit (resistance-capacitance circuit), and its electrical properties are very simple.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Starting from any initial state, the current flowing across either the conductance or the capacitance decays with an exponential time course, with a time constant of τ = RC, where C is the capacitance of the membrane patch, and R = 1/gnet is the net resistance.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For realistic situations, the time constant usually lies in the 1–100 millisecond range.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In most cases, changes in the conductance of ion channels occur on a faster time scale, so an RC circuit is not a good approximation; however, the differential equation used to model a membrane patch is commonly a modified version of the RC circuit equation.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] When the membrane potential of a cell goes for a long period of time without changing significantly, it is referred to as a resting potential or resting voltage.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This term is used for the membrane potential of non-excitable cells, but also for the membrane potential of excitable cells in the absence of excitation.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In excitable cells, the other possible states are graded membrane potentials (of variable amplitude), and action potentials, which are large, all-or-nothing rises in membrane potential that usually follow a fixed time course.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Excitable cells include neurons, muscle cells, and some secretory cells in glands.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Even in other types of cells, however, the membrane voltage can undergo changes in response to environmental or intracellular stimuli.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For example, depolarization of the plasma membrane appears to be an important step in programmed cell death.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The interactions that generate the resting potential are modeled by the Goldman equation.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This is similar in form to the Nernst equation shown above, in that it is based on the charges of the ions in question, as well as the difference between their inside and outside concentrations.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] However, it also takes into consideration the relative permeability of the plasma membrane to each ion in question.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In reality, there is some degree of permeability for several ions simultaneously, so the resting membrane potential is not the same as any one Nernst potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Rather, it is near a balance point of permeability for the prominent permeant ions (usually potassium, sodium, and chloride).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This can be represented by the Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz (GHK) voltage equation conceptually: ions with greater permeability contribute more to Vm.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This is why the resting potential is typically close to EK (because PK is typically the largest at rest), but slightly positive compared to ENa depending on sodium leak and other electrical activity.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The three ions that appear in this equation are potassium (K+), sodium (Na+), and chloride (Cl−).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Calcium is omitted, but can be added to deal with situations in which it plays a significant role.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Being an anion, the chloride terms are treated differently from the cation terms; the intracellular concentration is in the numerator, and the extracellular concentration in the denominator, which is reversed from the cation terms.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] *P*i stands for the relative permeability of the ion type i.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In essence, the Goldman formula expresses the membrane potential as a weighted average of the reversal potentials for the individual ion types, weighted by permeability.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] (Although the membrane potential changes about 100 mV during an action potential, the concentrations of ions inside and outside the cell do not change significantly.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] They remain close to their respective concentrations when then membrane is at resting potential.) In most animal cells, the permeability to potassium is much higher in the resting state than the permeability to sodium.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] As a consequence, the resting potential is usually close to the potassium reversal potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The permeability to chloride can be high enough to be significant, but, unlike the other ions, chloride is not actively pumped, and therefore equilibrates at a reversal potential very close to the resting potential determined by the other ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Values of resting membrane potential in most animal cells usually vary between the potassium reversal potential (usually around −80 mV) and around −40 mV.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The resting potential in excitable cells (capable of producing action potentials) is usually near −60 mV—more depolarized voltages would lead to spontaneous generation of action potentials.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Immature or undifferentiated cells show highly variable values of resting voltage, usually significantly more positive than in differentiated cells.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In such cells, the resting potential value correlates with the degree of differentiation: undifferentiated cells in some cases may not show any transmembrane voltage difference at all.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Maintenance of the resting potential can be metabolically costly for a cell because of its requirement for active pumping of ions to counteract losses due to leakage channels.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The cost is highest when the cell function requires an especially depolarized value of membrane voltage.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] For example, the resting potential in daylight-adapted blowfly (*Calliphora vicina*) photoreceptors can be as high as −30 mV.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This elevated membrane potential allows the cells to respond very rapidly to visual inputs; the cost is that maintenance of the resting potential may consume more than 20% of overall cellular ATP.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] On the other hand, the high resting potential in undifferentiated cells does not necessarily incur a high metabolic cost.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This apparent paradox is resolved by examination of the origin of that resting potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Little-differentiated cells are characterized by extremely high input resistance, which implies that few leakage channels are present at this stage of cell life.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] As an apparent result, potassium permeability becomes similar to that for sodium ions, which places resting potential in-between the reversal potentials for sodium and potassium as discussed above.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The reduced leakage currents also mean there is little need for active pumping in order to compensate, therefore low metabolic cost.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The classic approach is intracellular recording: one electrode is placed inside the cell and a reference electrode remains outside, allowing direct measurement of VmPerkins KL.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Cell-attached voltage-clamp and current-clamp recording and stimulation techniques in brain slices.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Modern electrophysiology frequently uses patch-clamp approaches, where a fine glass micropipette is pressed against the membrane to form a very high-resistance seal (giga-seal).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] This seal isolates a tiny patch of membrane so researchers can record specific electrical signals and, depending on the configuration, control which side of the membrane is exposed to different solutions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Voltage-clamp is useful for isolating sodium, potassium, calcium, or synaptic currents.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] As explained above, the potential at any point in a cell's membrane is determined by the ion concentration differences between the intracellular and extracellular areas, and by the permeability of the membrane to each type of ion.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The change in membrane potential can be either large or small, depending on how many ion channels are activated and what type they are, and can be either long or short, depending on the lengths of time that the channels remain open.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Changes of this type are referred to as **graded potentials**, in contrast to action potentials, which have a fixed amplitude and time course.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] As can be derived from the Goldman equation shown above, the effect of increasing the permeability of a membrane to a particular type of ion shifts the membrane potential toward the reversal potential for that ion.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Thus, opening Na+ channels shifts the membrane potential toward the Na+ reversal potential, which is usually around +100 mV.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Likewise, opening K+ channels shifts the membrane potential toward about −90 mV, and opening Cl− channels shifts it toward about −70 mV (resting potential of most membranes).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Thus, Na+ channels shift the membrane potential in a positive direction, K+ channels shift it in a negative direction (except when the membrane is hyperpolarized to a value more negative than the K+ reversal potential), and Cl− channels tend to shift it towards the resting potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Graded membrane potentials are particularly important in neurons, where they are produced by synapses—a temporary change in membrane potential produced by activation of a synapse by a single graded or action potential is called a postsynaptic potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Neurotransmitters that act to open Na+ channels typically cause the membrane potential to become more positive, while neurotransmitters that activate K+ channels typically cause it to become more negative; those that inhibit these channels tend to have the opposite effect.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Whether a postsynaptic potential is considered excitatory or inhibitory depends on the reversal potential for the ions of that current, and the threshold for the cell to fire an action potential (around −50 mV).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A postsynaptic current with a reversal potential above threshold, such as a typical Na+ current, is considered excitatory.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A current with a reversal potential below threshold, such as a typical K+ current, is considered inhibitory.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A current with a reversal potential above the resting potential, but below threshold, will not by itself elicit action potentials, but will produce subthreshold membrane potential oscillations.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Thus, neurotransmitters that act to open Na+ channels produce excitatory postsynaptic potentials, or EPSPs, whereas neurotransmitters that act to open K+ or Cl− channels typically produce inhibitory postsynaptic potentials, or IPSPs.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] When multiple types of channels are open within the same time period, their postsynaptic potentials summate (are added together).
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] From the viewpoint of biophysics, the *resting* membrane potential is merely the membrane potential that results from the membrane permeabilities that predominate when the cell is resting.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The above equation of weighted averages always applies, but the following approach may be more easily visualized.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] If the driving force is high, then the ion is being "pushed" across the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] If the permeability is high, it will be easier for the ion to diffuse across the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] So, in a resting membrane, while the driving force for potassium is low, its permeability is very high.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Sodium has a huge driving force but almost no resting permeability.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In this case, potassium carries about 20 times more current than sodium, and thus has 20 times more influence over *E*m than does sodium.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] However, consider another case—the peak of the action potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Here, permeability to Na is high and K permeability is relatively low.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Thus, the membrane moves to near *E*Na and far from *E*K.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The more ions are permeant the more complicated it becomes to predict the membrane potential.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] However, this can be done using the Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz equation or the weighted means equation.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] By plugging in the concentration gradients and the permeabilities of the ions at any instant in time, one can determine the membrane potential at that moment.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] What the GHK equations means is that, at any time, the value of the membrane potential will be a weighted average of the equilibrium potentials of all permeant ions.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The "weighting" is the ions relative permeability across the membrane.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] While cells expend energy to transport ions and establish a transmembrane potential, they use this potential in turn to transport other ions and metabolites such as sugar.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] The transmembrane potential of the mitochondria drives the production of ATP, which is the common currency of biological energy.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Cells may draw on the energy they store in the resting potential to drive action potentials or other forms of excitation.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] These changes in the membrane potential enable communication with other cells (as with action potentials) or initiate changes inside the cell, which happens in an egg when it is fertilized by a sperm.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Changes in the dielectric properties of plasma membrane may act as hallmark of underlying conditions such as diabetes and dyslipidemia.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] In neuronal cells, an action potential begins with a rush of sodium ions into the cell through sodium channels, resulting in depolarization, while recovery involves an outward rush of potassium through potassium channels.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] Both of these fluxes occur by passive diffusion.
[src:biophysics/membrane-potential] A dose of salt may trigger the still-working neurons of a fresh cut of meat into firing, causing muscle spasms.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] A recent study has also shown that certain enzymes, such as Hexokinase and Glucose Oxidase, are aggregating or fragmenting during catalysis.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] This changes their hydrodynamic size that can affect enhanced diffusion measurements.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] There are two major families of molecular motors that transport organelles throughout the cell.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] These families include the dynein family and the kinesin family.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] Both have very different structures from one another and different ways of achieving a similar goal of moving organelles around the cell.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] These distances, though only few micrometers, are all preplanned out using microtubules.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] and surround the entire volume of the cell.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] This in turn creates a "Rail system" of the whole cell and paths leading to its organelles.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] Because the motor events are stochastic, molecular motors are often modeled with the Fokker–Planck equation or with Monte Carlo methods.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] These theoretical models are especially useful when treating the molecular motor as a Brownian motor.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] As new technologies and methods are developed, it is expected that knowledge of naturally occurring molecular motors will be helpful in constructing synthetic nanoscale motors.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] Recently, chemists and those involved in nanotechnology have begun to explore the possibility of creating molecular motors *de novo.* These synthetic molecular motors currently suffer many limitations that confine their use to the research laboratory.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] However, many of these limitations may be overcome as our understanding of chemistry and physics at the nanoscale increases.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] One step toward understanding nanoscale dynamics was made with the study of catalyst diffusion in the Grubb's catalyst system.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] Other systems like the nanocars, while not technically motors, are also illustrative of recent efforts towards synthetic nanoscale motors.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] Other molecules can also behave as motors.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] Dye molecules can move directionally in gradients of polymer solution through favorable hydrophobic interactions.
[src:biophysics/molecular-motor] Another recent study has shown that dye molecules, hard and soft colloidal particles are able to move through gradient of polymer solution through excluded volume effects.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The folding of many proteins begins even during the translation of the polypeptide chain.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The amino acids interact with each other to produce a well-defined three-dimensional structure, known as the protein's native state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This structure is determined by the amino-acid sequence or primary structure.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The correct three-dimensional structure is essential to function, although some parts of functional proteins may remain unfolded, indicating that protein dynamics are important.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Failure to fold into a native structure generally produces inactive proteins, but in some instances, misfolded proteins have modified or toxic functionality.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Several neurodegenerative and other diseases are believed to result from the accumulation of amyloid fibrils formed by misfolded proteins, the infectious varieties of which are known as prions.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Many allergies are caused by the incorrect folding of some proteins because the immune system does not produce the antibodies for certain protein structures.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Denaturation of proteins is a process of transition from a folded to an unfolded state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] It happens in cooking, burns, proteinopathies, and other contexts.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Residual structure present, if any, in the supposedly unfolded state may form a folding initiation site and guide the subsequent folding reactions.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The duration of the folding process varies dramatically depending on the protein of interest.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] When studied outside the cell, the slowest folding proteins require many minutes or hours to fold, primarily due to proline isomerization, and must pass through a number of intermediate states, like checkpoints, before the process is complete.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] On the other hand, very small single-domain proteins with lengths of up to a hundred amino acids typically fold in a single step.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Time scales of milliseconds are the norm, and the fastest known protein folding reactions are complete within a few microseconds.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The folding time scale of a protein depends on its size, contact order, and circuit topology.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Understanding and simulating the protein folding process has been an important challenge for computational biology since the late 1960s.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The primary structure of a protein, its linear amino-acid sequence, determines its native conformation.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The specific amino acid residues and their position in the polypeptide chain are the determining factors for which portions of the protein fold closely together and form its three-dimensional conformation.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The amino acid composition is not as important as the sequence.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The essential fact of folding, however, remains that the amino acid sequence of each protein contains the information that specifies both the native structure and the pathway to attain that state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This is not to say that nearly identical amino acid sequences always fold similarly.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Conformations differ based on environmental factors as well; similar proteins fold differently based on where they are found.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Formation of a secondary structure is the first step in the folding process that a protein takes to assume its native structure.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Characteristic of secondary structure are the structures known as alpha helices and beta sheets that fold rapidly because they are stabilized by intramolecular hydrogen bonds, as was first characterized by Linus Pauling.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Formation of intramolecular hydrogen bonds provides another important contribution to protein stability. α-helices are formed by hydrogen bonding of the backbone to form a spiral shape (refer to figure on the right).
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The β pleated sheet is a structure that forms with the backbone bending over itself to form the hydrogen bonds (as displayed in the figure to the left).
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The hydrogen bonds are between the amide hydrogen and carbonyl oxygen of the peptide bond.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] There exists anti-parallel β pleated sheets and parallel β pleated sheets where the stability of the hydrogen bonds is stronger in the anti-parallel β sheet as it hydrogen bonds with the ideal 180 degree angle compared to the slanted hydrogen bonds formed by parallel sheets.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The α-Helices and β-Sheets are commonly amphipathic, meaning they have a hydrophilic and a hydrophobic portion.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This ability helps in forming tertiary structure of a protein in which folding occurs so that the hydrophilic sides are facing the aqueous environment surrounding the protein and the hydrophobic sides are facing the hydrophobic core of the protein.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Secondary structure hierarchically gives way to tertiary structure formation.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Once the protein's tertiary structure is formed and stabilized by the hydrophobic interactions, there may also be covalent bonding in the form of disulfide bridges formed between two cysteine residues.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] These non-covalent and covalent contacts take a specific topological arrangement in a native structure of a protein.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Tertiary structure of a protein involves a single polypeptide chain; however, additional interactions of folded polypeptide chains give rise to quaternary structure formation.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Tertiary structure may give way to the formation of quaternary structure in some proteins, which usually involves the "assembly" or "coassembly" of subunits that have already folded; in other words, multiple polypeptide chains could interact to form a fully functional quaternary protein.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Folding is a spontaneous process that is mainly guided by hydrophobic interactions, formation of intramolecular hydrogen bonds, van der Waals forces, and it is opposed by conformational entropy.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The folding time scale of an isolated protein depends on its size, contact order, and circuit topology.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Inside cells, the process of folding often begins co-translationally, so that the N-terminus of the protein begins to fold while the C-terminal portion of the protein is still being synthesized by the ribosome; however, a protein molecule may fold spontaneously during or after biosynthesis.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] While these macromolecules may be regarded as "folding themselves", the process also depends on the solvent (water or lipid bilayer), the concentration of salts, the pH, the temperature, the possible presence of cofactors and of molecular chaperones.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Proteins will have limitations on their folding abilities by the restricted bending angles or conformations that are possible.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] These allowable angles of protein folding are described with a two-dimensional plot known as the Ramachandran plot, depicted with psi and phi angles of allowable rotation.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Protein folding must be thermodynamically favorable within a cell in order for it to be a spontaneous reaction.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Since it is known that protein folding is a spontaneous reaction, then it must assume a negative Gibbs free energy value.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Gibbs free energy in protein folding is directly related to enthalpy and entropy.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] For a negative delta G to arise and for protein folding to become thermodynamically favorable, then either enthalpy, entropy, or both terms must be favorable.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Minimizing the number of hydrophobic side-chains exposed to water is an important driving force behind the folding process.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The hydrophobic effect is the phenomenon in which the hydrophobic chains of a protein collapse into the core of the protein (away from the hydrophilic environment).
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In an aqueous environment, the water molecules tend to aggregate around the hydrophobic regions or side chains of the protein, creating water shells of ordered water molecules.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] An ordering of water molecules around a hydrophobic region increases order in a system and therefore contributes a negative change in entropy (less entropy in the system).
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The water molecules are fixed in these water cages which drives the hydrophobic collapse, or the inward folding of the hydrophobic groups.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The hydrophobic collapse introduces entropy back to the system via the breaking of the water cages which frees the ordered water molecules.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The multitude of hydrophobic groups interacting within the core of the globular folded protein contributes a significant amount to protein stability after folding, because of the vastly accumulated van der Waals forces (specifically London Dispersion forces).
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The hydrophobic effect exists as a driving force in thermodynamics only if there is the presence of an aqueous medium with an amphiphilic molecule containing a large hydrophobic region.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The strength of hydrogen bonds depends on their environment; thus, H-bonds enveloped in a hydrophobic core contribute more than H-bonds exposed to the aqueous environment to the stability of the native state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In proteins with globular folds, hydrophobic amino acids tend to be interspersed along the primary sequence, rather than randomly distributed or clustered together.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] However, proteins that have recently been born de novo, which tend to be intrinsically disordered, show the opposite pattern of hydrophobic amino acid clustering along the primary sequence.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Molecular chaperones are a class of proteins that aid in the correct folding of other proteins *in vivo*.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Chaperones exist in all cellular compartments and interact with the polypeptide chain in order to allow the native three-dimensional conformation of the protein to form; however, chaperones themselves are not included in the final structure of the protein they are assisting in.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Chaperones may assist in folding even when the nascent polypeptide is being synthesized by the ribosome.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Chaperones are not to be confused with folding catalyst proteins, which catalyze chemical reactions responsible for slow steps in folding pathways.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Examples of folding catalysts are protein disulfide isomerases and peptidyl-prolyl isomerases that may be involved in formation of disulfide bonds or interconversion between cis and trans stereoisomers of peptide group.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Chaperones are shown to be critical in the process of protein folding *in vivo* because they provide the protein with the aid needed to assume its proper alignments and conformations efficiently enough to become "biologically relevant".
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] A fully denatured protein lacks both tertiary and secondary structure, and exists as a so-called random coil.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Under certain conditions some proteins can refold; however, in many cases, denaturation is irreversible.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Cells sometimes protect their proteins against the denaturing influence of heat with enzymes known as heat shock proteins (a type of chaperone), which assist other proteins both in folding and in remaining folded.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Heat shock proteins have been found in all species examined, from bacteria to humans, suggesting that they evolved very early and have an important function.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Some proteins never fold in cells at all except with the assistance of chaperones which either isolate individual proteins so that their folding is not interrupted by interactions with other proteins or help to unfold misfolded proteins, allowing them to refold into the correct native structure.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This function is crucial to prevent the risk of precipitation into insoluble amorphous aggregates.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The external factors involved in protein denaturation or disruption of the native state include temperature, external fields (electric, magnetic), molecular crowding, and even the limitation of space (i.e. confinement), which can have a big influence on the folding of proteins.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] High concentrations of solutes, extremes of pH, mechanical forces, and the presence of chemical denaturants can contribute to protein denaturation, as well.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] These individual factors are categorized together as stresses.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Chaperones are shown to exist in increasing concentrations during times of cellular stress and help the proper folding of emerging proteins as well as denatured or misfolded ones.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Under some conditions proteins will not fold into their biochemically functional forms.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Temperatures above or below the range that cells tend to live in will cause thermally unstable proteins to unfold or denature (this is why boiling makes an egg white turn opaque).
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Protein thermal stability is far from constant, however; for example, hyperthermophilic archaea have been found that grow at temperatures as high as 122 °C, which of course requires that their full complement of vital proteins and protein assemblies be stable at that temperature or above.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The bacterium *E. coli* is the host for bacteriophage T4, and the phage encoded gp31 protein (P17313) appears to be structurally and functionally homologous to *E. coli* chaperone protein GroES and able to substitute for it in the assembly of bacteriophage T4 virus particles during infection.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Like GroES, gp31 forms a stable complex with GroEL chaperonin that is absolutely necessary for the folding and assembly in vivo of the bacteriophage T4 major capsid protein gp23.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Some proteins have multiple native structures, and change their fold based on some external factors.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] For example, the KaiB protein switches fold throughout the day, acting as a clock for cyanobacteria.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] It has been estimated that around 0.5–4% of PDB (Protein Data Bank) proteins switch folds.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] A protein is considered to be misfolded if it cannot achieve its normal native state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This can be due to mutations in the amino acid sequence or to a disruption of the normal folding process by external factors.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The misfolded protein typically contains beta sheets (β-sheets) that are organized in a supramolecular arrangement known as a cross-β structure.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] These β-sheet-rich assemblies are very stable, very insoluble, and generally resistant to proteolysis.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The structural stability of these fibrillar assemblies is caused by extensive interactions between the protein monomers, formed by backbone hydrogen bonds between their β-strands.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The misfolding of proteins can trigger the further misfolding and accumulation of other proteins into aggregates or oligomers.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The increased levels of aggregated proteins in the cell leads to formation of amyloid-like structures which can cause neurodegenerative disorders and cell death.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The amyloids are fibrillary structures that contain intermolecular hydrogen bonds which are highly insoluble and made from converted protein aggregates.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Therefore, the proteasome pathway may not be efficient enough to degrade the misfolded proteins prior to aggregation.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Misfolded proteins can interact with one another and form structured aggregates and gain toxicity through intermolecular interactions.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] These age onset degenerative diseases are associated with the aggregation of misfolded proteins into insoluble, extracellular aggregates and/or intracellular inclusions including cross-β amyloid fibrils.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] It is not completely clear whether the aggregates are the cause or merely a reflection of the loss of protein homeostasis, the balance between synthesis, folding, aggregation and protein turnover.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Recently the European Medicines Agency approved the use of Tafamidis or Vyndaqel (a kinetic stabilizer of tetrameric transthyretin) for the treatment of transthyretin amyloid diseases.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This suggests that the process of amyloid fibril formation (and not the fibrils themselves) causes the degeneration of post-mitotic tissue in human amyloid diseases.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Misfolding and excessive degradation instead of folding and function leads to a number of proteinopathies, diseases such as antitrypsin-associated emphysema, cystic fibrosis and the lysosomal storage diseases, where loss of function is the origin of the disorder.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] While protein replacement therapy has historically been used to correct the latter disorders, an emerging approach is to use pharmaceutical chaperones to fold mutated proteins to render them functional.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] While inferences about protein folding can be made through mutation studies, typically, experimental techniques for studying protein folding rely on the gradual unfolding or folding of proteins and observing conformational changes using standard non-crystallographic techniques.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] X-ray crystallography is one of the more efficient and important methods for attempting to decipher the three dimensional configuration of a folded protein.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] To be able to conduct X-ray crystallography, the protein under investigation must be located inside a crystal lattice.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] To place a protein inside a crystal lattice, one must have a suitable solvent for crystallization, obtain a pure protein at supersaturated levels in solution, and precipitate the crystals in solution.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Once a protein is crystallized, X-ray beams can be concentrated through the crystal lattice which would diffract the beams or shoot them outwards in various directions.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] These exiting beams are correlated to the specific three-dimensional configuration of the protein enclosed within.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The X-rays specifically interact with the electron clouds surrounding the individual atoms within the protein crystal lattice and produce a discernible diffraction pattern.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Only by relating the electron density clouds with the amplitude of the X-rays can this pattern be read and lead to assumptions of the phases or phase angles involved that complicate this method.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Without the relation established through a mathematical basis known as Fourier transform, the "phase problem" would render predicting the diffraction patterns very difficult.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Emerging methods like multiple isomorphous replacement use the presence of a heavy metal ion to diffract the X-rays into a more predictable manner, reducing the number of variables involved and resolving the phase problem.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy is a highly sensitive method for studying the folding state of proteins.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Three amino acids, phenylalanine (Phe), tyrosine (Tyr) and tryptophan (Trp), have intrinsic fluorescence properties, but only Tyr and Trp are used experimentally because their quantum yields are high enough to give good fluorescence signals.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Both Trp and Tyr are excited by a wavelength of 280 nm, whereas only Trp is excited by a wavelength of 295 nm.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Because of their aromatic character, Trp and Tyr residues are often found fully or partially buried in the hydrophobic core of proteins, at the interface between two protein domains, or at the interface between subunits of oligomeric proteins.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In this apolar environment, they have high quantum yields and therefore high fluorescence intensities.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Upon disruption of the protein's tertiary or quaternary structure, these side chains become more exposed to the hydrophilic environment of the solvent, and their quantum yields decrease, leading to low fluorescence intensities.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] For Trp residues, the wavelength of their maximal fluorescence emission also depend on their environment.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy can be used to characterize the equilibrium unfolding of proteins by measuring the variation in the intensity of fluorescence emission or in the wavelength of maximal emission as functions of a denaturant value.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The denaturant can be a chemical molecule (urea, guanidinium hydrochloride), temperature, pH, pressure, etc.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The equilibrium between the different but discrete protein states, i.e. native state, intermediate states, unfolded state, depends on the denaturant value; therefore, the global fluorescence signal of their equilibrium mixture also depends on this value.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] One thus obtains a profile relating the global protein signal to the denaturant value.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The profile of equilibrium unfolding may enable one to detect and identify intermediates of unfolding.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] General equations have been developed by Hugues Bedouelle to obtain the thermodynamic parameters that characterize the unfolding equilibria for homomeric or heteromeric proteins, up to trimers and potentially tetramers, from such profiles.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy can be combined with fast-mixing devices such as stopped flow, to measure protein folding kinetics, generate a chevron plot and derive a Phi value analysis.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Circular dichroism is one of the most general and basic tools to study protein folding.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Circular dichroism spectroscopy measures the absorption of circularly polarized light.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In proteins, structures such as alpha helices and beta sheets are chiral, and thus absorb such light.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The absorption of this light acts as a marker of the degree of foldedness of the protein ensemble.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This technique has been used to measure equilibrium unfolding of the protein by measuring the change in this absorption as a function of denaturant concentration or temperature.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] A denaturant melt measures the free energy of unfolding as well as the protein's m value, or denaturant dependence.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] A temperature melt measures the denaturation temperature (Tm) of the protein.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] As for fluorescence spectroscopy, circular-dichroism spectroscopy can be combined with fast-mixing devices such as stopped flow to measure protein folding kinetics and to generate chevron plots.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The more recent developments of vibrational circular dichroism (VCD) techniques for proteins, currently involving Fourier transform (FT) instruments, provide powerful means for determining protein conformations in solution even for very large protein molecules.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Such VCD studies of proteins can be combined with X-ray diffraction data for protein crystals, FT-IR data for protein solutions in heavy water (D2O), or quantum computations.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Protein nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is able to collect protein structural data by inducing a magnet field through samples of concentrated protein.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In NMR, depending on the chemical environment, certain nuclei will absorb specific radio-frequencies.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Because protein structural changes operate on a time scale from ns to ms, NMR is especially equipped to study intermediate structures in timescales of ps to s.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Some of the main techniques for studying proteins structure and non-folding protein structural changes include COSY, TOCSY, HSQC, time relaxation (T1 & T2), and NOE.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] NOE is especially useful because magnetization transfers can be observed between spatially proximal hydrogens are observed.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Different NMR experiments have varying degrees of timescale sensitivity that are appropriate for different protein structural changes.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] NOE can pick up bond vibrations or side chain rotations, however, NOE is too sensitive to pick up protein folding because it occurs at larger timescale.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Because protein folding takes place in about 50 to 3000 s−1 CPMG Relaxation dispersion and chemical exchange saturation transfer have become some of the primary techniques for NMR analysis of folding.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In addition, both techniques are used to uncover excited intermediate states in the protein folding landscape.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] To do this, CPMG Relaxation dispersion takes advantage of the spin echo phenomenon.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This technique exposes the target nuclei to a 90 pulse followed by one or more 180 pulses.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] As the nuclei refocus, a broad distribution indicates the target nuclei is involved in an intermediate excited state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] By looking at Relaxation dispersion plots the data collect information on the thermodynamics and kinetics between the excited and ground.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Saturation Transfer measures changes in signal from the ground state as excited states become perturbed.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] It uses weak radio frequency irradiation to saturate the excited state of a particular nuclei which transfers its saturation to the ground state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This signal is amplified by decreasing the magnetization (and the signal) of the ground state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The main limitations in NMR is that its resolution decreases with proteins that are larger than 25 kDa and is not as detailed as X-ray crystallography.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Additionally, protein NMR analysis is quite difficult and can propose multiple solutions from the same NMR spectrum.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In a study focused on the folding of an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis involved protein SOD1, excited intermediates were studied with relaxation dispersion and Saturation transfer.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] SOD1 had been previously tied to many disease causing mutants which were assumed to be involved in protein aggregation, however the mechanism was still unknown.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] By using Relaxation Dispersion and Saturation Transfer experiments many excited intermediate states were uncovered misfolding in the SOD1 mutants.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Dual polarisation interferometry is a surface-based technique for measuring the optical properties of molecular layers.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Similar to circular dichroism, the stimulus for folding can be a denaturant or temperature.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The study of protein folding has been greatly advanced in recent years by the development of fast, time-resolved techniques.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Experimenters rapidly trigger the folding of a sample of unfolded protein and observe the resulting dynamics.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Fast techniques in use include ultrafast mixing of solutions, photochemical methods, and laser temperature jump spectroscopy.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Among the many scientists who have contributed to the development of these techniques are Heinrich Roder, Terry Oas, Harry Gray, Martin Gruebele, Brian Dyer, William Eaton, Sheena Radford, Chris Dobson, Alan Fersht, Bengt Nölting and Lars Konermann.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Proteolysis is routinely used to probe the fraction unfolded under a wide range of solution conditions (e.g. fast parallel proteolysis (FASTpp).
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Single molecule techniques such as optical tweezers and AFM have been used to understand protein folding mechanisms of isolated proteins as well as proteins with chaperones.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Optical tweezers have been used to stretch single protein molecules from their C- and N-termini and unfold them to allow study of the subsequent refolding.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] It was discovered – using single molecule optical tweezers measurement – that calcium-bound vWF acts as a shear force sensor in the blood.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Shear force leads to unfolding of the A2 domain of vWF, whose refolding rate is dramatically enhanced in the presence of calcium.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] It has also been shown that the simple src SH3 domain accesses multiple unfolding pathways under force.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Biotin painting enables condition-specific cellular snapshots of (un)folded proteins.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Biotin 'painting' shows a bias towards predicted Intrinsically disordered proteins.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Computational studies of protein folding includes three main aspects related to the prediction of protein stability, kinetics, and structure.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] A 2013 review summarizes the available computational methods for protein folding.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In 1969, Cyrus Levinthal noted that, because of the very large number of degrees of freedom in an unfolded polypeptide chain, the molecule has an astronomical number of possible conformations.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] An estimate of 3300 or 10143 was made in one of his papers.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Based upon the observation that proteins fold much faster than this, Levinthal then proposed that a random conformational search does not occur, and the protein must, therefore, fold through a series of meta-stable intermediate states.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The configuration space of a protein during folding can be visualized as an energy landscape.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In addition, the acquisition of the folded state had to become a sufficiently fast process.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Even though nature has reduced the level of *frustration* in proteins, some degree of it remains up to now as can be observed in the presence of local minima in the energy landscape of proteins.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] A consequence of these evolutionarily selected sequences is that proteins are generally thought to have globally "funneled energy landscapes" (a term coined by José Onuchic) that are largely directed toward the native state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This "folding funnel" landscape allows the protein to fold to the native state through any of a large number of pathways and intermediates, rather than being restricted to a single mechanism.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The theory is supported by both computational simulations of model proteins and experimental studies, and it has been used to improve methods for protein structure prediction and design.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The description of protein folding by the leveling free-energy landscape is also consistent with the 2nd law of thermodynamics.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Physically, thinking of landscapes in terms of visualizable potential or total energy surfaces simply with maxima, saddle points, minima, and funnels, rather like geographic landscapes, is perhaps a little misleading.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The relevant description is really a high-dimensional phase space in which manifolds might take a variety of more complicated topological forms.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The unfolded polypeptide chain begins at the top of the funnel where it may assume the largest number of unfolded variations and is in its highest energy state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Energy landscapes such as these indicate that there are a large number of initial possibilities, but only a single native state is possible; however, it does not reveal the numerous folding pathways that are possible.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] A different molecule of the same exact protein may be able to follow marginally different folding pathways, seeking different lower energy intermediates, as long as the same native structure is reached.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Different pathways may have different frequencies of utilization depending on the thermodynamic favorability of each pathway.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] This means that if one pathway is found to be more thermodynamically favorable than another, it is likely to be used more frequently in the pursuit of the native structure.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] As the protein begins to fold and assume its various conformations, it always seeks a more thermodynamically favorable structure than before and thus continues through the energy funnel.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Formation of secondary structures is a strong indication of increased stability within the protein, and only one combination of secondary structures assumed by the polypeptide backbone will have the lowest energy and therefore be present in the native state of the protein.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Among the first structures to form once the polypeptide begins to fold are alpha helices and beta turns, where alpha helices can form in as little as 100 nanoseconds and beta turns in 1 microsecond.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] There exists a saddle point in the energy funnel landscape where the transition state for a particular protein is found.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The transition state in the energy funnel diagram is the conformation that must be assumed by every molecule of that protein if the protein wishes to finally assume the native structure.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] No protein may assume the native structure without first passing through the transition state.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The transition state can be referred to as a variant or premature form of the native state rather than just another intermediary step.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The folding of the transition state is shown to be rate-determining, and even though it exists in a higher energy state than the native fold, it greatly resembles the native structure.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Within the transition state, there exists a nucleus around which the protein is able to fold, formed by a process referred to as "nucleation condensation" where the structure begins to collapse onto the nucleus.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Several large-scale computational projects, such as Rosetta@home, Folding@home and Foldit, target protein folding.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Long continuous-trajectory simulations have been performed on Anton, a massively parallel supercomputer designed and built around custom ASICs and interconnects by D.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The longest published result of a simulation performed using Anton as of 2011 was a 2.936 millisecond simulation of NTL9 at 355 K.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Such simulations are currently able to unfold and refold small proteins (<150 amino acids residues) in equilibrium and predict how mutations affect folding kinetics and stability.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] In 2020 a team of researchers that used AlphaFold, an artificial intelligence (AI) protein structure prediction program developed by DeepMind placed first in CASP, a long-standing structure prediction contest.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] The team achieved a level of accuracy much higher than any other group.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] It scored above 90% for around two-thirds of the proteins in CASP's global distance test (GDT), a test that measures the degree of similarity between the structure predicted by a computational program, and the empirical structure determined experimentally in a lab.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] A score of 100 is considered a complete match, within the distance cutoff used for calculating GDT.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] AlphaFold's protein structure prediction results at CASP were described as "transformational" and "astounding".
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Some researchers noted that the accuracy is not high enough for a third of its predictions, and that it does not reveal the physical mechanism of protein folding for the protein folding problem to be considered solved.
[src:biophysics/protein-folding] Nevertheless, it is considered a significant achievement in computational biology and great progress towards a decades-old grand challenge of biology, predicting the structure of proteins.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] A **single-molecule experiment** is an experiment that investigates the properties of individual molecules.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Single-molecule studies may be contrasted with measurements on an ensemble or bulk collection of molecules, where the individual behavior of molecules cannot be distinguished, and only average characteristics can be measured.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Indeed, since the 1990s, many techniques for probing individual molecules have been developed.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] The first single-molecule experiments were patch clamp experiments performed in the 1970s, but these were limited to studying ion channels.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Today, systems investigated using single-molecule techniques include the movement of myosin on actin filaments in muscle tissue and the spectroscopic details of individual local environments in solids.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Biological polymers' conformations have been measured using atomic force microscopy (AFM).
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Using force spectroscopy, single molecules (or pairs of interacting molecules), usually polymers, can be mechanically stretched, and their elastic response recorded in real time.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] In the gas phase at ultralow pressures, single-molecule experiments have been around for decades, but in the condensed phase only since 1989 with the work by W.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] One year later, Michel Orrit and Jacky Bernard were able to show also the detection of the absorption of single molecules by their fluorescence.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Many techniques have the ability to observe one molecule at a time, most notably mass spectrometry, where single ions are detected.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] In addition, one of the earliest means of detecting single molecules, came about in the field of ion channels with the development of the patch clamp technique by Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann (who later went on to win the Nobel prize for their seminal contributions).
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] However, the idea of measuring conductance to look at single molecules placed a serious limitation on the kind of systems which could be observed.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Fluorescence is a convenient means of observing one molecule at a time, mostly due to the sensitivity of commercial optical detectors, capable of counting single photons.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] The most studied protein has been the class of myosin/actin enzymes found in muscle tissues.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Through single-molecule techniques the step mechanism has been observed and characterized in many of these proteins.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] In 1997, single-molecule detection was demonstrated with surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS) by Katrin Kneipp, H.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Perelman and others at MIT and independently by S.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] The MIT team used non-resonance Raman excitation and surface enhancement with silver nanoclusters to detect single cresyl violet molecules, while the team at Indiana University used resonance Raman excitation and surface enhancement with silver nanoparticles to detect single rhodamine 6G molecules.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Nanomanipulators such as the atomic force microscope are also suited to single-molecule experiments of biological significance, since they work on the same length scale of most biological polymers.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Besides, atomic force microscopy (AFM) is appropriate for the studies of synthetic polymer molecules.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] AFM provides a unique possibility of 3D visualization of polymer chains.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] For instance, AFM tapping mode is gentle enough for the recording of adsorbed polyelectrolyte molecules (for example, 0.4 nm thick chains of poly(2-vinylpyridine)) under liquid medium.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] The location of two-chain-superposition correspond in these experiments to twice the thickness of single chain (0.8 nm in the case of the mentioned example).
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] At the application of proper scanning parameters, conformation of such molecules remain unchanged for hours that allows the performance of experiments under liquid media having various properties.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Furthermore, by controlling the force between the tip and the sample high resolution images can be obtained.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Optical tweezers have also been used to study and quantify DNA-protein interactions.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Single-molecule fluorescence spectroscopy uses the fluorescence of a molecule for obtaining information on its environment, structure, and position.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] The technique affords the ability of obtaining information otherwise not available due to ensemble averaging (that is, a signal obtained when recording many molecules at the same time represents an average property of the molecules' dynamics).
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] The results in many experiments of individual molecules are two-state trajectories.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] As in the case of single molecule fluorescence spectroscopy, the technique known as single channel recording can be used to obtain specific kinetic information—in this case about ion channel function—that is not available when ensemble recording, such as whole-cell recording, is performed.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Specifically, ion channels alternate between conducting and non-conducting classes, which differ in conformation.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Therefore, the functional state of ion channels can be directly measured with sufficiently sensitive electronics, provided that proper precautions are taken to minimize noise.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] In turn, each of these classes may be divided into one or more kinetic states with direct bearing on the underlying function of the ion channel.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] In a minimal model for an ion channel, there are two states: open and closed.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] However, other states are often needed in order to accurately represent the data, including multiple closed states as well as inactive and/or desensitized states, which are non-conducting states that can occur even in the presence of stimulus.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Single fluorophores can be chemically attached to biomolecules, such as proteins or DNA, and the dynamics of individual molecules can be tracked by monitoring the fluorescent probe.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Spatial movements within the Rayleigh limit can be tracked, along with changes in emission intensity and/or radiative lifetime, which often indicate changes in local environment.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] For instance, single-molecule labeling has yielded a vast quantity of information on how kinesin motor proteins move along microtubule strands in muscle cells.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Single-molecule imaging in live cells reveals interesting information about protein dynamics under its physiological environment.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Several biophysical parameters about protein dynamics can be quantified such as diffusion coefficient, mean squared displacements, residence time, the fraction of bound and unbound molecules, and target-search mechanism of protein binding to its target site in the live cell.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] In single-molecule fluorescence resonance energy transfer, the molecule is labeled in (at least) two places.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] A laser beam is focused on the molecule exciting the first probe.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] When this probe relaxes and emits a photon, it has a chance of exciting the other probe.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] The efficiency of the absorption of the photon emitted from the first probe in the second probe depends on the distance between these probes.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Since the distance changes with time, this experiment probes the internal dynamics of the molecule.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] When looking at data related to individual molecules, one usually can construct propagators, and jumping time probability density functions, of the first order, the second order and so on, whereas from bulk experiments, one usually obtains the decay of a correlation function.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] From the information contained in these unique functions (obtained from individual molecules), one can extract a relatively clear picture on the way the system behaves; e.g. its kinetic scheme, or its potential of activity, or its reduced dimensions form.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] In particular, one can construct (many properties of) the reaction pathway of an enzyme when monitoring the activity of an individual enzyme.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Additionally, significant aspects regarding the analysis of single molecule data—such as fitting methods and tests for homogeneous populations—have been described by several authors.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] Single-molecule techniques impacted optics, electronics, biology, and chemistry.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] In the biological sciences, the study of proteins and other complex biological machinery was limited to ensemble experiments that nearly made impossible the direct observation of their kinetics.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] For example, it was only after single molecule fluorescence microscopy was used to study kinesin-myosin pairs in muscle tissue that direct observation of the walking mechanisms were understood.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] These experiments, however, have for the most part been limited to in vitro studies, as useful techniques for live cell imaging have yet to be fully realized.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] The promise of single molecule in vivo imaging, however, brings with it an enormous potential to directly observe bio-molecules in native processes.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] These techniques are often targeted for studies involving low-copy proteins, many of which are still being discovered.
[src:biophysics/single-molecule-experiment] These techniques have also been extended to study areas of chemistry, including the mapping of heterogeneous surfaces.
